            <ns0:div type="apparatus" resp="#AA">
                <ns0:listApp>
                    <ns0:app>
                        <ns0:note>Text from autopsy</ns0:note>
                    </ns0:app>
                    <ns0:app loc="line 2">
                        <ns0:note>
                            There is no immediately clear answer as to what the sign "&#8579;", a reverse C, symbolises here; cf.<ns0:ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000146">ISic000146</ns0:ref>and
                            <ns0:ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000174">ISic000174</ns0:ref>; also CIL 6.15139 (Rome) for analogous use, as pointed out by Bivona (1994). Understanding &#8579; as signifying 'circiter' is one attractive interpretation.
                        </ns0:note>
                    </ns0:app>
                </ns0:listApp>
            </ns0:div>
            <ns0:div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#TA">
                <ns0:p>To the Shades of the Underworld. Cornelia Scepsis; she lived about(?) 38 years. Auctus erected this for his most dutiful wife.</ns0:p>
            </ns0:div>
            <ns0:div type="commentary" resp="#AA">
                <ns0:p>The husband of the deceased, Auctus, is known only by his cognomen. It is probable that Auctus is the same individual as identified <ns0:ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000161">ISic000161</ns0:ref> and <ns0:ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000164">ISic000164</ns0:ref>, all found at the same time and in the same location, from which we can discern his name: L. Cornelius Auctus. Corneliae are common in Thermae Himeraeae, although the cognomen Scepsis is unknown in Sicily</ns0:p>
            </ns0:div>
